At 1:33 You might notice those stripes are somewhat mottled. That sometimes means the caterpillar has OE, a protozoan parasite. Most pupae with OE emerge crippled, often deformed wings. Those that don’t spread the disease, where the spore falls from their abdomens like glitter onto eggs/milkweed leaves.
In California, where this was filmed, the resident milkweed is the nonnative tropical milkweed (A. curassavica). It’s a garden-favorite for its scarlet to golden flowers that attract all pollinators. But because many regions of CA don’t have frigid weather to “kill off” tropical milkweed, unlike northern states, OE spores can build up on the plant. And since tropical milkweed can grow year round, more monarchs stay in SoCal instead of migrating. This in turn spreads more OE spores, leading to a ~30% OE rate in SoCal monarchs.
So um, what are the options?
1. Cut down tropical milkweed every fall, so new growth is ready in the spring.
2. Grow native milkweed.

The monarch population is on the decline. With that, a cultural symbol and a much-needed pollinator.

The outside of a butterfly as a pupa/chrysalis is similar to the larval stage or adult (imago) in that it’s the animal’s exoskeleton.

P. polyxenes is common, but those who rear monarchs do the world a favor: the population has dramatically declined in the past few decades and extinction is a real threat.
